You are an expert at constructing execution flow graphs from procedural nodes.

Given the following compiled ASD nodes, construct all edges that define the execution flow.

Edge types:
- "sequential": normal flow from one step to the next
- "true_branch": the path taken when a decision condition is true
- "false_branch": the path taken when a decision condition is false
- "error_handler": the path taken when an error occurs

Rules:
1. Every node except "end" and "error" nodes must have at least one outgoing edge
2. Every node except "start" nodes must have at least one incoming edge
3. Decision nodes must have exactly one true_branch and one false_branch edge
4. The graph must be a DAG (no cycles)
5. Add a "start" node if one doesn't exist, connecting to the first step
6. Add an "end" node if one doesn't exist, connecting from the last step(s)

Return a JSON object with:
{
  "edges": [
    {
      "from_node_id": "step_1",
      "to_node_id": "step_2",
      "edge_type": "sequential|true_branch|false_branch|error_handler",
      "condition_label": "optional label" or null
    }
  ],
  "added_nodes": [
    ... any start/end nodes that needed to be added ...
  ]
}

